    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Baccharis salicifolia</i> includes the Colorado Desert (322C), Klamath Mountains (M261A), Modoc Plateau (M261G), and Sonoran Desert (322B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac, Ae, Ag-h, Aj-l). Stands occur along the Salinas River, Coyote Creek, and a number of larger streams in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). Stands are widespread along creeks throughout the section. Stands are described in the Diablo Range (Evens et al. 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Stands are common on the undammed portions of creeks, rivers, and streams throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ac-d). Stands occur in the Owens Valley along creeks and along the Amargosa River near Shoshone.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Di). Stands occur in the upper Owens River drainage near Bishop.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aj, Al-m). Stands are scattered along the Russian River and some other streams in the southern portion of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb-f). Stands occur along intermittent streams and some of the larger rivers in the more inland portion of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). Stands occur along the Elder, Stony, Thomes and other larger creeks that flow through the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ep, Er-s). Stands occur at lower montane elevations (Potter 2005) and along creeks in the southern and southeastern portions.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fb, Fd). Stands occur primarily south of the Kings River (Potter 2005). Some stands are on the Feather and Merced rivers further north.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fa-f). Small stands occur adjacent to springs and ephemeral streams throughout the section; sometimes these are associated with <i>B. emoryi</i> and <i>B. sergiloides.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands occur throughout the section with descriptions from the Santa Clara River parkway (Stillwater Sciences and URS 2007), San Dieguito River drainage (Evens and San 2005), and Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf-g, Bi-l, Bn-p). Stands occur in riparian areas with descriptions from the eastern slopes of the Peninsular Ranges in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b) and from western Riverside Co. (Boyd et al. 1995, Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Baccharis salicifolia </i>grows in areas that are invaded by <i>Tamarix </i>spp. Flooding in this alliance is variable in complexity, intensity, and severity. Floods occur regularly during the winter to spring with larger events at 7-10 year intervals. </div>
</div>

    

    

